      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> The HTTP information above is collected for all non-encrypted connections."
    },
    {
      "content": "For TLS connections, this information is only captured when the ‘Deep Inspection’ setting is turned on in the portal.",
      "pos": [
        4835,
        4952
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The setting is ‘ON’ by default.",
      "pos": [
        4953,
        4984
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more details, see below, and <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Getting Started With Cloud App Discovery<ept id=\"p1\">](http://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/30962.getting-started-with-cloud-app-discovery.aspx)</ept>",
      "pos": [
        4985,
        5172
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How the agent works",
      "pos": [
        5188,
        5207
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The agent installation includes two components:",
      "pos": [
        5209,
        5256
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A user-mode component",
      "pos": [
        5260,
        5281
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A kernel-mode driver component (Windows Filtering Platform driver)",
      "pos": [
        5285,
        5351
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the agent is first installed it stores a machine-specific trusted certificate on the machine which it then uses to establish a secure connection with the Cloud App Discovery service.",
      "pos": [
        5355,
        5542
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The agent periodically retrieves policy configuration from the Cloud App Discovery service over this secure connection.",
      "pos": [
        5548,
        5667
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The policy includes information about which cloud applications to monitor and whether auto-updating should be enabled, among other things.",
      "pos": [
        5673,
        5811
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As Web traffic is sent and received on the machine from Internet Explorer and Chrome, the Cloud App Discovery agent analyzes the traffic and extracts the relevant metadata (see the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Data collected by the agent<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> section above).",
      "pos": [
        5813,
        6041
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Every minute, the agent uploads the collected metadata to the Cloud App Discovery service over an encrypted channel.",
      "pos": [
        6047,
        6163
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The driver component intercepts the encrypted traffic and inserts itself into the encrypted stream.",
      "pos": [
        6165,
        6264
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "More details in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Intercepting data from encrypted connections (Deep inspection)<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> section below.",
      "pos": [
        6265,
        6366
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Respecting user privacy",
      "pos": [
        6373,
        6396
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Our goal is to provide administrators the tools to set the balance between detailed optics into application usage and user privacy as appropriate for their organization.",
      "pos": [
        6398,
        6567
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To that end, we provide the following knobs in the settings page in the Portal:",
      "pos": [
        6568,
        6647
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6651,
        6789
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Data Collection<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Administrators can choose to specify which applications or application categories they want to get discovery data on."
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Deep Inspection<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Administrators can chose to specify if the agent collects HTTP traffic for SSL/TLS connections (aka <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>'Deep Inspection'<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>).",
      "pos": [
        6793,
        6937
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "More on this in the next section.",
      "pos": [
        6938,
        6971
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6975,
        7202
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Consent Options<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Administrators can use the Cloud App Discovery portal to choose whether to notify users of the data collection by the agent, and whether to require user consent before the agent starts collecting user data."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        7204,
        7336
      ],
      "content": "The Cloud App Discovery endpoint agent only collects the information described in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Data collected by the agent<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> section above."
    },
    {
      "content": "Intercepting data from encrypted connections (Deep inspection)",
      "pos": [
        7343,
        7405
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As we mentioned earlier, administrators can configure the agent to monitor data from encrypted connections ('deep inspection').",
      "pos": [
        7406,
        7533
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "TLS (<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Transport Layer Security<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/aa380516%28v=vs.85%29.aspx)</ept>) is one of the most common protocols in use on the Internet today.",
      "pos": [
        7534,
        7711
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By encrypting communication with TLS, a client can establish a secure and private communication channel with a web server; TLS provides essential protection for passing authentication credentials and prevent the disclosure of sensitive information.",
      "pos": [
        7712,
        7960
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While the end-to-end secure encrypted channel provided by TLS enables important security and privacy protection, the protocol is often abused for malicious or nefarious purposes.",
      "pos": [
        7962,
        8140
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "So much so, in fact, that TLS is often referred to as the “universal firewall-bypass protocol”.",
      "pos": [
        8141,
        8236
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The root of the problem is that most firewalls are unable to inspect TLS communication because the application-layer data is encrypted with SSL.",
      "pos": [
        8237,
        8381
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Knowing this, attackers frequently leverage TLS to deliver malicious payloads to a user confident that even the most intelligent application-layer firewalls are completely blind to TLS and must simply relay TLS communication between hosts.",
      "pos": [
        8382,
        8621
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "End users frequently leverage TLS to bypass access controls enforced by their corporate firewalls and proxy servers, using it to connect to public proxies and for tunneling non-TLS protocols through the firewall that might otherwise be blocked by policy.",
      "pos": [
        8622,
        8876
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deep inspection allows the Cloud App Discovery agent to act as a trusted man-in-the-middle.",
      "pos": [
        8878,
        8969
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When a client request is made to access an HTTPS protected resource, the Endpoint Agent driver intercepts the connection and establishes a new connection to the destination server to retrieves its SSL certificate on behalf of the client.",
      "pos": [
        8970,
        9207
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The agent then verifies that the certificate can be trusted (by checking that it was not revoked, and performing other certificate checks), and if these pass, the Endpoint Agent then copies the information from the server certificate and creates its own server certificate -- known as an interception certificate -- using that information.",
      "pos": [
        9208,
        9547
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The interception certificate is signed on-the-fly by the endpoint agent with a root certificate, which is installed in the Windows trusted certificate store.",
      "pos": [
        9548,
        9705
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This self-signed root certificate is marked non-exportable and is ACL’d to administrators.",
      "pos": [
        9706,
        9796
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is intended to never leave the machine on which it was created.",
      "pos": [
        9797,
        9863
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the end-user’s client application receives the interception certificate, it will trust it because it can successfully validate the certificate chain all the way to the root certificate.",
      "pos": [
        9864,
        10054
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This process is mostly transparent from an end-user’s point of view with a few caveats as described below.",
      "pos": [
        10055,
        10161
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By enabling deep inspection, the Cloud App Discovery Endpoint Agent can decrypt and inspect TLS encrypted communications, allowing the service to reduce noise and provide insights about the usage of the encrypted cloud apps.",
      "pos": [
        10163,
        10387
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A word of caution",
      "pos": [
        10394,
        10411
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Before turning on deep inspection, it is strongly suggested that you communicate your intentions to your legal and HR departments and obtain their consent.",
      "pos": [
        10412,
        10567
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Inspecting end user’s private encrypted communications can be a sensitive subject, for obvious reasons.",
      "pos": [
        10568,
        10671
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Before a production roll-out of deep inspection, make certain that your corporate security and acceptable use policies have been updated to indicate that encrypted communication will be inspected.",
      "pos": [
        10672,
        10868
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "User notification and exemption of sites deemed sensitive (e.g. banking and medical sites) may also be necessary if you configure Cloud App Discovery to monitor them.",
      "pos": [
        10869,
        11035
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As mentioned above, administrators can use the Cloud App Discovery portal to choose whether to notify users of the data collection by the agent, and whether to require user consent before the agent starts collecting user data.",
      "pos": [
        11036,
        11262
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Known issues and drawbacks",
      "pos": [
        11268,
        11294
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are a few cases where TLS interception may impact the end user experience:",
      "pos": [
        11295,
        11375
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Extended Validation (EV) certificates render the address bar of the web browser green to act as a visual clue that you are visiting a trusted web site.",
      "pos": [
        11379,
        11530
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "TLS inspection cannot duplicate EV in the certificate it issues to the client, so web sites that use EV certificates will work normally but the address bar will not display green.",
      "pos": [
        11531,
        11710
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Public key pinning (also known as certificate pinning) are designed to help protect users from man-in-the-middle attacks and rogue certificate authorities.",
      "pos": [
        11716,
        11871
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the root certificate for a pinned site does not match one of the known good CA's, the browser rejects the connection with an error.",
      "pos": [
        11872,
        12008
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since TLS interception is, in fact, a man-in-the-middle, these connections will fail.",
      "pos": [
        12009,
        12094
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If users click the lock icon in the browser address bar browser to inspect the site information, they will not see a chain ending in the certificate authority used to sign the website certificate, but instead a certificate chain ending with the Windows trusted certificate store.",
      "pos": [
        12098,
        12377
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To reduce the occurrences of these issues, we keep track of cloud services and client applications known to use extended validation or public key pinning and instruct the Endpoint Agent to avoid intercepting impacted connections.",
      "pos": [
        12379,
        12608
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Even in these cases, however, you will still receive reports of the use of these cloud apps and the volume of data being transferred, but since they are not deep inspected, no details about how the apps were used will be available.",
      "pos": [
        12609,
        12840
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sending data to Cloud App Discovery",
      "pos": [
        12846,
        12881
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once metadata has been collected by the agent, it is cached on the machine for up to one minute or until the cached data reaches a size of 5MB.",
      "pos": [
        12883,
        13026
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is then compressed and sent over a secure connection to the Cloud App Discovery service.",
      "pos": [
        13027,
        13118
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the agent is unable to communicate with the Cloud App Discovery service for any reason, the collected metadata is stored in a local file cache that can only be accessed by privileged users on the machine (such as the Administrators group).",
      "pos": [
        13120,
        13362
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The agent automatically attempts to resend the cached metadata until it has successfully been received by the Cloud App Discovery service.",
      "pos": [
        13368,
        13506
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Receiving the data at the service end",
      "pos": [
        13513,
        13550
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The agents authenticate to the Cloud App Discovery service using the machine specific client authentication certificate referenced above and forwards data over an encrypted channel.",
      "pos": [
        13552,
        13733
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Cloud App Discovery service’s analytics pipeline processes metadata for each customer separately by logically partitioning it through all stages of the analytics pipeline.",
      "pos": [
        13739,
        13914
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The analyzed metadata drives the various reports in the portal.",
      "pos": [
        13915,
        13978
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The unprocessed metadata and the analyzed metadata are stored for up to 180 days.",
      "pos": [
        13980,
        14061
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, customers can choose to capture the analyzed metadata in an Azure blob storage account of their choosing.",
      "pos": [
        14062,
        14180
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is useful for offline analysis of metadata as well as longer retention of the data.",
      "pos": [
        14181,
        14269
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Accessing the data using the Azure portal",
      "pos": [
        14274,
        14315
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In an effort to keep the metadata collected secure, by default only global administrators of the tenant have access to the Cloud App Discovery feature in the Azure portal.",
      "pos": [
        14317,
        14488
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, administrators can choose to delegate this access to other users or groups.",
      "pos": [
        14494,
        14578
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        14584,
        14773
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> For more details, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Getting Started With Cloud App Discovery<ept id=\"p1\">](http://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/30962.getting-started-with-cloud-app-discovery.aspx)</ept>"
    },
    {
      "content": "Any user accessing the data in the portal, must be licensed with an Azure AD Premium license.",
      "pos": [
        14780,
        14873
      ]
    },
